            "mimeType": "application/json",
            "size": 1644,
            "text": "{\"model\":\"claude-sonnet-4-5-20250929\",\"id\":\"msg_01UKr53oqiWuWQCia8zuuwTW\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Great question! Here's how Google Ads works with your headlines and descriptions:\\n\\n**Google automatically mixes and matches them** to find the best-performing combinations. Here's what happens:\\n\\n- **Up to 3 headlines** show at once (out of your 6)\\n- **Up to 2 descriptions** show at once (out of your 4)\\n- Google's algorithm tests different combinations to see which gets the most clicks\\n\\n**Why this matters:**\\n- Each headline should work independently and make sense on its own\\n- Descriptions should complement any headline combination\\n- You don't control which specific pairings show—Google optimizes this automatically based on performance data\\n\\n**What you'll see:**\\nThe Ad Preview at the top shows you *one sample combination*, but real users will see different variations. This testing approach helps Google learn what resonates best with your audience.\\n\\n**Pro tip:** Since they pair dynamically, avoid repeating the exact same information in multiple headlines or descriptions. Instead, vary your messaging angles (benefits, features, urgency, social proof) so any combination tells a compelling story.\\n\\nWould you like me to generate your headlines and descriptions now, keeping this pairing strategy in mind?\"}],\"stop_reason\":\"end_turn\",\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":2786,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":0,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":0,\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":0,\"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens\":0},\"output_tokens\":260,\"service_tier\":\"standard\"}}"
