            "mimeType": "application/json",
            "params": [],
            "text": "{\"model\":\"rerank-v3.5\",\"query\":\"preview headlines preferred pinning\",\"documents\":[\"How does the Ad Preview at the top work?\\n\\nAt the top of the page you'll see an Ad Preview card:\\nIt updates as you edit your headlines and details.\\nIt shows a sample combination of your content, not every possible version.\\nDifferent customers in Google Search may see different headline/description combinations than the one in the preview.\\n\\nThe preview is meant to help you visualize the ad and check for typos, tone, and messaging—not to represent all variations.\",\"Can I bulk add headlines instead of typing them one by one?\\n\\nYes. On the Content page you can paste several headlines at once instead of typing them one by one.\\nA simple workflow:\\nPrepare your list\\nCreate your headlines in a text editor or spreadsheet.\\nPut each headline on its own line and keep them under 30 characters.\\nPaste into the headline input\\nClick in the main \\\"Enter headline\\\" field.\\nPaste your list of headlines.\\nWe will detect line breaks and split them into separate headline rows.\\nReview and select\\nCheck that each new row looks correct and is within the character limit.\\nUse \\\"Select 3–15\\\" to choose which ones are active for your ad.\\nYou can still edit or delete any individual headline after a bulk paste, and you can combine bulk-added headlines with AI-generated suggestions.\",\"How many headlines should I actually use?\\n\\nWe recommend:\\nMinimum: 3 (required by Google)\\nBetter: 5–8\\nMaximum: 15\\nMore high-quality options give Google more combinations to test, which can improve performance over time. However, avoid filling all 15 with only tiny variations. Aim for meaningful differences in message or angle.\",\"Will Launch10 check if my headlines comply with Google Ads policies?\\n\\nWe do our best to keep suggestions within common Google Ads guidelines, but:\\nGoogle makes the final decision about ad approval.\\nIf Google flags or disapproves a headline, you may need to adjust wording (for example, remove prohibited claims, sensitive content, or certain trademarks).\\nIf a headline is rejected, you can:\\nEdit it manually, or\\nUse \\\"Refresh Suggestions\\\" and pick an alternative.\",\"How does Launch10's AI use my answers from earlier steps to suggest headlines?\\n\\nWe use everything you shared during the Brainstorm and Landing Page steps, including:\\nYour business type and services\\nYour ideal customer\\nYour tone and style preferences\\nAny offers, pricing, or location details\\nLaunch10 uses this context to generate headlines that:\\nMatch your landing page content\\nInclude relevant search phrases\\nStay consistent with your page, so the ad and page feel like one seamless experience\\nYou can fully edit these suggestions. Once you change and lock a headline, we treat your version as the source of truth.\",\"How does this Content page relate to the \\\"Highlights\\\" tab?\\n\\nOn the Content tab you write the main ad text that appears in almost every impression.\\nOn the Highlights tab (next step):\\nYou will usually add structured information such as features, service types, or callouts, depending on the configuration.\\nThese often map to Google ad extensions (now called \\\"assets\\\"), which can show in addition to your headlines and descriptions.\\nYou should complete the Content tab first, since this is the foundation of your ad.\",\"What does \\\"Refresh Suggestions\\\" do for Headlines?\\n\\n\\\"Refresh Suggestions\\\" will:\\nAsk the AI to generate a new set of headline ideas, based on your latest business info and page content.\\nLeave any existing headlines you have edited and locked in place.\\nAdd the new suggestions below your current options (or replace only the ones that are still untouched), depending on the final product behavior.\\nIf you manually wrote or edited a headline and then locked it, that content will not be overwritten without your action.\",\"Do Highlights always show with my ad?\\n\\nNo. Google decides when to show each asset based on:\\nThe customer's device and context.\\nThe space available on the results page.\\nThe expected impact on performance.\\nSometimes customers will see your ad with both Unique Features and Offerings, sometimes with only one type, and sometimes with just the core text. This is normal.\",\"How are Unique Features different from Headlines and Details?\\n\\nHeadlines are the main clickable blue text in your ad.\\nDetails (or descriptions) are longer sentences that explain what you do.\\nUnique Features are very short, punchy phrases that stack on top of your existing ad text.\\nThink of Unique Features as quick \\\"bonus reasons\\\" to choose you. They should not repeat entire sentences from your descriptions. Instead, they should call out standout perks.\",\"What happens if I leave Unique Features blank?\\n\\nIn many cases your ad can still run with just headlines and descriptions, but:\\nYou will miss an opportunity to take up more space in search results.\\nYour ad may feel less compelling compared to competitors using callouts.\\nWe encourage you to add at least 2 Unique Features because they are a quick way to improve performance.\"],\"top_n\":5}"
          },
          "queryString": [],
          "url": "https://api.cohere.com/v2/rerank"
        },
